Journal of Criminal Justice 33 (2005) 153 – 163
Impact of drug use on inmate misconduct: A multilevel analysis
Shanhe Jiang*
Department of Criminal Justice, University of Toledo, Mail Stop 119, Toledo, OH, 43606, United States

Abstract
Despite the importance of drug use problems among offenders, relatively little was known about whether drug use history affected inmate behavior in prison. Using data from the 1997 survey of inmates in state facilities in the U.S., this study examined the following relationships: the effect of drug use prior to incarceration on substance rule violations per month during incarceration and the effect of drug use prior to incarceration on non-substance rule violations per month in prison. This study revealed that the variable drug use history was a significant predictor of substance rule violations per month and of nonsubstance rule violations per month in prison. The implications of the findings are also discussed. D 2004 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.

Introduction
The U.S. began a new war on drugs in the mid-1980s1 (Inciardi, 1990, p. xiv, 2002, p. 248; Jensen & Gerber, 1998, p. 6; McWilliams, 1990; Webb & Brown, 1998, pp. 49–50), which was marked by the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986. The law set mandatory minimum sentences for certain drug offenses. bThe underlying logic of the mandatory minimum sentences was to create an incentive for law enforcement to focus on drug dealers and to differentiate serious from major traffickersQ (Everett, 1998, p. 97). The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 extended these efforts to users (Everett, 1998, p. 97). The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, the 1988 revisions, and the ongoing war on drugs (see Inciardi, 2002, Chap. 9 for more details) led to substantial changes in the criminal justice systems in the U.S. These changes included the increased pressure on police to have more arrests for drug violations, stiff mandatory sentences for drug offenses, and extremely punitive sentences for crack-related offenses (Jensen & Gerber, 1998; Webb & Brown, 1998).
