There was a dramatic increase in the number of drug offenders in prison as a result of this new war on drugs (Bureau of Justice Statistics, 2001; Jensen & Gerber, 1998; Schwartz & Travis, 1997, p. 259). In 1985, one year before the 1986 Anti-Drug Abuse Act, there were approximately 38,900 drug offenders or roughly 8.6 percent of prisoners (Schwartz & Travis, 1997, p. 259). By 1997, the year of the data collected and used in this study, drug offenders accounted for over 250,000 prisoners; they constituted 21 percent of state prisoners and over 60 percent of federal prisoners (Bureau of Justice Statistics, 1999a). For Black prisoners, the current offense was 3.6 times more likely to be a drug offense in 1997 than in 1986 while for White prisoners, it was 1.5 times more likely in 1997 than in 1986 (Bureau of Justice Statistics, 1993, 1999b). In addition, 83 percent of state inmates in the same year reported past drug use (Bureau of Justice Statistics, 1999a).
This dramatic increase greatly contributed to changes in prison conditions. First, racial proportions changed. In 1985, Black non-Hispanic prisoners represented an estimated 45 percent of all prisoners with sentences of more than one year, while White non-Hispanic prisoners accounted for 40 percent. In 1997, the same categories were 47 percent and 33 percent, respectively (Bureau of Justice Statistics, 2000, p. iv). Second, prisons became more crowded. Despite huge prison construction projects, state prisons were operating at

