Although there was a high proportion of drug offenders in prison and a very high percent of past drug use among the prisoner population, relatively little was known about whether, in general, drug use history affected inmate behavior in prison and, in particular, inmate drug rule violations in prison. This study investigated these effects.
Prior empirical research
This section reviews the empirical studies of the relationship between drug use and inmate adjustment to prison. Table 1 presents a summary of relevant studies.

Among these studies, four (MacDonald, 1999; Thomas, 1977; Thomas & Cage, 1977; Winfree, Mays, Crowley, & Peat, 1994) focused on the relationship between drug use and inmate adjustment. The other five studies (Cao, Zhao, & Dine, 1997; Craddock, 1996; Flanagan, 1983; Goetting & Howsen, 1986; Light, 1990) included drug use as just one of the independent variables. Since the study done by Akers, Hayner, and Gruninger (1974), which used substance use as a dependent variable, was closely related to Thomas’ (1977) and Thomas and Cage’s (1977) studies, the following review will first describe the study done by Akers et al. Then the four studies with a focus on the effect of drug use will be reviewed. Besides drug use, the review will be presented based on sample size, research site, dependent variable, and drug-related findings.
Akers et al. (1974) was the first significant work on prison drug use (Thomas & Cage, 1977). The study presented analysis of data from the seven U.S. prisons, which were the units of analysis. Using prison drug use as one of the two dependent variables, the analysis suggested that the amount of drug use among inmates was more a function of the type of prison which held them than that of the social characteristics which they brought with them from the outside. Two limitations were apparent in this study. The first was that the study used a nonrandom small sample, which limited its generalizability. Second, Akers and his associates obtained information on the number of inmates

