Thomas and Cage (1977) extended the study done by Akers et al. (1974) through collecting information on selfreported drug use and on whether drug use began before or after confinement. They surveyed 273 young adult male felons from a relatively small medium-security penitentiary. This same data set was used by Thomas (1977) and Thomas and Cage. Thomas examined the impact of pre-prison drug use on three attitude variables – prisonization, opposition to prison, and criminal identification among inmates. In this study, a comparison of the mean prisonization level revealed no statistically significant difference among the three groups – inmates reporting no drug use, inmates reporting pre-prison drug use only, and inmates reporting prison drug use. The study also showed that those who had pre-prison drug use only or who had continued to use drugs afterwards were significantly more oppositional to the prison than those with no drug experience. Finally, the study found that those who reported prison drug use were significantly higher in their levels of criminal identification than those who never used drugs. With a focus on the relationship between pre-prison drug use and prison drug use, Thomas and Cage found that the variables reflecting pre-prison involvement in drug use had the highest associations with prison drug use.
These two studies also had apparent limitations. The sample was not random and came from one prison. The highest level of statistics used by Thomas and Cage (1977) was bivariate association. Thus, a causal relationship between drug use history and prison drug use could not be established from the study since the relationship between the two variables might be spurious. In Thomas’ (1977) study, prison drug use was not treated as a dependent variable. Therefore, even though its descriptive statistics suggested a strong bivariate association between drug use prior to confinement and drug use during confinement the causal relationship was not guaranteed.
In order to examine the effect of drug use history on inmate adjustment to prison, Winfree and his associates (1994) collected information from a nonrandom sample of seventy-two male inmates from a medium-security, stateoperated prison. The four dependent variables in the study were inmate code adoption and inmate adjustment to three categories of staff: caseworkers, mental health staff, and custody staff. All four variables were measures of inmate attitudes or values. Their study revealed mixed results about the relationship between drug use history and the four dependent variables. For example, self-defined addicts were more likely to give mental health staff higher evaluations than were non-addicts while hedonistic drug users were less likely to reject caseworkers than were non-hedonistic drug users.3 In addition, drug use history did not affect inmate code adoption at all.

MacDonald (1999) intended to fill some of the gaps in the literature on the factors that influenced inmate misconduct, such as data from a single or a few prisons and the lack of quantitative studies. Using two random samples of youths paroled from sixteen California Youth Authority institutions, this study examined an integrated model of selected importation and deprivation factors on inmate acts of violence and drug use. The study found that those with prior criminal history of drug-related offenses were significantly less likely to engage in violent activity. This study, however, did not find a significant relationship between preprison drug use and drug misconduct in institutions.
Overall, research about the effect of drug use history on inmate prison adjustment was sparse. As described above, the findings on the effect were mixed (see also Table 1). Several limitations were inherent in the literature. First, except for Macdonald’s (1999) study, existing studies of the effect of drug use history on inmate misconduct in prison did not distinguish between substance and non-substance rule violations in prison. Thus, they could not determine if drug use history affected substance or non-substance rule violations in prison since the findings for overall inmate misconduct might be different from those for substance or non-substance rule violations.
Second, previous research was generally too narrow in scope for their results to be of much use in generalizing for theory and policy discussion. Among the nine studies shown in Table 1, only one (Goetting & Howsen, 1986) used a nationwide sample. The samples in all other studies were drawn from either only one state or one facility. One limitation of nonrandom sampling was clear: the results from a sample could not be generalized to the larger population.
Finally, there was the lack of quantitative studies examining the relationship between drug use history and inmate misconduct (MacDonald, 1999; Thomas & Cage, 1977). Among the quantitative studies, the pooled regression models or aggregate regression models with ordinary least squares estimation were often used even though they were inappropriate methods for multilevel count data, such as rule violations in prison.
This study sought to overcome the aforementioned limitations through the examination of the effect of drug use history on inmate adjustment to prison, contributing to the existing literature in several ways. Examining the impact of pre-prison drug use on inmate substance and nonsubstance rule violations would help specify whether drug use history affected substance and non-substance rule violations in prison. Since this study used the data from the 1997 Survey of Inmates in State and Federal Correctional Facilities in the U.S., which was a nationwide survey, it helped overcome the limitations of the narrow scope of samples in previous research.
Finally, the dependent variables in this study were count (or nonnegative integer-valued) and the data used in this study were multilevel. Hierarchical generalized linear

