modeling (HGLM) was the most appropriate technique for analyzing this type of data (Huebner, 2003; Raudenbush & Bryk, 2002, Chap. 10). Therefore, HGLM was used in this study. Using this technique helped to overcome the limitations of the lack of quantitative analysis and of using traditional linear models in the existing literature. As Long (1997) pointed out, bCount variables are often treated as though they are continuous and the linear regression model is appliedQ (p. 217). The use of linear regression model for count variables violated the assumptions of linearity and normality (Raudenbush & Bryk, 2002, pp. 291–292) and could result in inefficient, inconsistent, and biased estimates (Long, 1997, p. 217). HGLM using Poisson-based estimations, however, computed the probability of the observed count of rule violations, based on the fitted value for the mean count (Long, 1997, p. 218; Osgood, 2000, p. 36). It successfully addressed the most serious problems that arose in the OLS analyses.
Problems with traditional linear models for rule violations were not only from using the OLS estimate, but also from aggregating and disaggregating. Aggregating regression aggregated individual-level variables to the higher level and did the analysis on the higher level. The main problem with this approach was to completely ignore the withingroup variations (Bryk & Raudenbush, 1992, p. xiv; Kreft & de Leeuw, 1998, p. 22). Pooled regression completely ignored the within-group variation and disaggregated all higher order variables to the individual level. The main problem with this approach was the violation of the assumption of independence (Bryk & Raudenbush, 1992, p. xiv).4 HGLM allowed a researcher to statistically adjust the problem although it certainly was not a solution to all the data analysis problems (Bryk & Raudenbush, 1992, p. xiv; Wooldredge, Griffin, & Pratt, 2001, p. 215).
Conceptual background
Despite the relative paucity of previous research on the relationship between drug use history and inmate prison adjustment, the literature provided not only some empirical findings as reviewed above, but also conceptual frameworks. There were two major theories in explaining inmate adjustment to prison: the deprivation and importation models. The deprivation model focused on the influence of institutional environmental conditions. It was thought that the effects of organizational factors overshadowed individual differences in determining inmates’ behavior. The prison environment encouraged the process of prisonization through adaptations to the bpains of imprisonmentQ (Sykes, 1958). The inmates’ adjustment to these pains led to the development of anti-administration orientations. The orientations in turn led to inmate rule violations (Harer & Steffensmeier, 1996; Wright, 1991).
In contrast to the deprivation model, the importation model, proposed by Irwin (1970) and Irwin and Cressey

(1962), and advanced by Jacobs (1974, 1976) and Carroll (1974), emphasized the impact of individual and demographic factors, such as age and race, in addition to preprison socialization and experiences which were carried into the prison by the individual inmate. It was argued that these imported factors influenced inmates’ orientations, attitudes, and behaviors in the correctional setting.
Some scholars extended these two general theories to predict the effect of pre-prison drug use on specific prison rule violations, such as substance rule violations (pre-prison drug useYsubstance rule violations in prison). Sykes (1958, pp. 80–81) suggested that if inmates were confronted with a painfully frustrating situation caused by a prison, they could attempt to solve their problem by psychological withdrawal, such as drug use. He implied that drug use in prison could be interpreted as one functional adaptation to the prison pressure (Akers et al., 1974; MacDonald, 1999) rather than as a continuity of pre-prison drug use.
According to the importation model, however, prison substance rule violations could be caused by pre-prison drug use experience. Irwin (1970, pp. 15–23) did make reference to drug use in discussing the in-prison behavior of the bdope fiendQ and the bhead.Q bSince these are role types defined by pre-prison behavior, it is clear that he sees their drug use as simply an extension of behavior patterns established before imprisonmentQ (Akers et al., 1974). Following the logic of the importation model, Thomas (1977) and Thomas and Cage (1977) explicitly argued that the emergence of substance use in prison was not a direct consequence of prison-specific factors. Pre-prison drug use was imported into the prison world. Those predisposed to drug use would continue their use in prison. Their findings also provided support for the importation model. MacDonald (1999) hypothesized that inmates with a history of drug problems might be more apt to be involved in substance use infractions in prison. Findings from his study, however, reported no effect of pre-prison drug use on prison drug use.
Specific relationships between pre-prison drug use and prison non-substance rule violations were also suggested by the deprivation and importation models (pre-prison drug useYnon-substance rule violations in prison). Sykes (1958, pp. 80–81) suggested that, in response to the pains of imprisonment, inmates could try to rebel in a violent manner. His study (1958) implied that inmate violent behavior in prison could be seen as a consequence of the institution itself, regardless of individual pre-prison experience such as drug use history. MacDonald (1999), however, hypothesized that inmates with a history of drug use problems might be less prone to getting involved in violent confrontations. His findings also provided a support for the hypothesis.
Research hypotheses
Based on the above conceptual frameworks, this study primarily examined the effects of pre-prison drug use on

