prison substance rule violations and on prison non-substance rule violations. This study hypothesized that pre-prison drug use affected substance rule violations in prison. It also hypothesized that pre-prison drug use affected non-substance rule violations in prison. The first effect was expected to be stronger than the second one. The study controlled for those commonly expected individual level predictors of rule infractions in prison, which included age, race, crime history, and sentence length. It also controlled for prison level variables such as security level, prison size, and type of prison – prisons with only male inmates, prisons with only female inmates, and prisons with both male and female inmates. Security level was commonly used as a deprivation variable at the individual level. Doing so was to disaggregate a higher order level (prison level) variable to the individual (inmate) level. This approach violated bthe assumption of independence of observations that is basic for the classical statistical techniquesQ (Bryk & Raudenbush, 1992, p. xiv) since the inmates selected from the same prison were likely to be more similar than the inmates selected from different prisons (Kreft & de Leeuw, 1998, p. 9). The variable btype of prisonQ was included to check whether male prisons and female prisons had different rule violations. Prison size might affect inmate behavior. Thus, it was included in this study.
Data collection5
The data set used in this study was from the Survey of Inmates in State and Federal Correctional Facilities, 1997.6 The survey consisted of two distinct surveys – the 1997 Survey of Inmates in State Correctional Facilities (SISCF) and the 1997 survey of Inmates in Federal Correctional Facilities; however, the present analysis focused solely on the state survey, providing nationally representative data on all state prison inmates in the U.S.
The inmate sample for the 1997 SISCF was selected from a universe of 1,409 state prisons. The sample design for the SISCF survey employed a stratified, two-stage selection. The first stage separated all correctional facilities into two sampling frames: one for prisons with male inmates and one for prisons with female inmates. Prisons holding males and females were included on both lists and treated independently in sample selections based on their population of male or female prisoners as relevant. The state prison universe included 1,131 prisons with male inmates only, 131 with female inmates only, and 147 with both male and female inmates. Overall, 280 state prisons were selected for the sample. Of the 280 prisons, two female inmate facilities had closed before interviewing and three female inmate facilities refused to participate. A total of 275 state prisons participated in the survey, including 207 male inmate prisons, 47 female inmate prisons, and 21 prisons holding both male and female inmates.

In the second stage, inmates were randomly selected for interviews. Census Bureau interviewers selected each institutional sample by systematically sampling a list provided by the facility of all inmates using a bed on the previous night. In the SISCF, 12,269 males and 3,116 females were sampled. A total of 1,100 inmates in the state survey refused to participate, resulting in 7.2 percent second stage non-response among state inmates. As a result, more than 14,000 interviews were completed for the state survey.
The interview used computer-assisted personal interviewing (CAPI) and took about one hour. With CAPI, computers provided questions for the interviewer. Before the interview, inmates were told verbally and in writing that participation was voluntary and that all information provided would be held in confidence. Participants were assured that the survey was solely for statistical purposes and that no individual who participated would be identified in survey results (Harlow, Snell, & Mumola, 2000, pp. 69–70).
There were several factors that might influence the reliability and validity of this large-scale self-report survey of prison inmates, including the inability to obtain information about all cases in the sample, inmate inability to provide correct information, inmate inability to recall information, and errors made in data collection such as in recording or coding the data and in processing the data. In addition, the respondents might consciously elect to lie (Wooldredge, 1987) because of suspicions of institutional retaliation.
Measurement
Dependent variables
This study had two dependent variables. They were prison substance rule violations per month and prison nonsubstance rule violations per month for each inmate since his/her most recent admission to prison. They were composite and count variables. Two steps were used to form both variables. The first step was to get the summation from several types of rule violations in the 1997 survey of state inmates. Then the summation was divided by time served to date of interview to obtain a rate. Prison substance rule violations per month for each inmate were the combination of drug, alcohol, and other substance use violations. Prison non-substance rule violations per month for each inmate were the combination of possession of a weapon, possession of stolen property, verbal and physical assault on an officer/staff, escape/attempted escape, and any other major or minor violations.
Independent variables
There were two levels of independent variables. The Level 1 (or inmate level) variables included drug use history and other commonly used variables – age at interview, race,

