crime history, and length of sentence. Drug use history was measured by regular poly-drug use prior to incarceration. This variable was the summation of types of drugs an inmate had ever used regularly before his or her incarceration. The original question asked was bHave you ever used (heroin) once a week or more for at least a month?Q The same question was used to ask the inmates about the following twelve types of drugs: other opiates, methamphetamine such as ice or crank, other amphetamines, methaqualone such as Quaaludes, barbiturates, tranquilizers such as Valium, crack, cocaine, PCP, LSD or other hallucinogens, marijuana or hashish, and other drugs. bOther drugsQ included any drugs not mentioned above. The alpha coefficient for this variable was .78.6.7
Age at interview was measured in years. In the 1997 SISCF, race included categories of White, Black/AfricanAmerican, Asian and Pacific Islander, American Indian, and other. This study focused on Black (score = 0) and White (score = 1). Crime history was measured by the number of prior sentences to probation or incarceration. The categories for this variable were no prior sentence (score = 0), one prior sentence (score = 1), two prior sentences (score = 2), three to five prior sentences (score = 3), six to ten prior sentences (score = 4), and eleven or more prior sentences (score = 5). Length of sentence referred to current sentence. In the 1997 survey, it was measured in years, plus other sentence categories, such as life, life plus additional years, life without parole, and death. The computation of length of sentence in this study excluded nonnumerical categories – life, life plus additional years, life without parole, and death.
The Level 2 (or prison level) variables included prison size and four dummy variables. Prison size was measured by final population count on sampling day. Two of the dummies were created from the variable prison security level. They were minimum and medium security levels. The reference category was maximum-security level. Two other dummies were created from the variable type of prison. They were prisons holding female inmates and prisons holding both male and female inmates. The variable prisons for male inmates was the reference category.
