The results for the substance rule violation rate are presented in Table 3.
Visual inspection of Table 3 showed that drug use history (REGUUSE) positively affected log substance rule violations per month. To be more specific, for every additional type of drug use prior to prison, an inmate’s mean substance rule violation rate increased by 14 percent (= 100 [exp(.1341) À 1], holding all other variables constant. The finding provided support for the hypothesis formed above. It was also consistent with MacDonald’s (1999).
Besides drug use history, several other Level 1 variables were also statistically significant. Age was negatively related to log substance rule violation rate. White inmates were more likely to commit substance rule violations per month. Furthermore, being a White inmate increased the expected substance rule violation rate by a factor of 1.60

(= exp(.4712), holding all other variables constant. The variable crime history was positively related to log substance rule violation rate, with a magnitude of .1702. That is, the more prior sentences, the more substance rule violations per month. Finally, the variable sentence length was not statistically significant.
At the prison level, Table 3 showed that five variables were statistically significant. The variable mean age (MeanAge) was negatively related to the substance rule violation rate, with a magnitude of À.0775. That is, for every unit change in the average age of inmates, there was a decrease of mean substance rule violation rate by 7 percent (= 100[exp(À.0775)]À1), holding all other variables constant. Compared to maximum-security level (the reference group), the dummy variable medium-security level had a negative effect. Furthermore, being a medium-security level prison decreased the expected substance rule violation rate by 31 percent (=100[exp(À.3771)]À1), holding all other variables constant. The effect for the dummy variable prisons holding female inmates (FPrison) was negative, with a magnitude of À.7151, while the effect for the dummy variable prisons holding both male and female inmates (CoPrison) was positive, with a magnitude of .6979. The effect of prison size (PSize) was significant and positive but weak, with a magnitude of À.0002. The full model explained 8 percent of the variance at Level 2.
