Comparing the substance and non-substance rule violation models showed that, at the inmate level, drug use history affected both substance rule violation rate and nonsubstance rule violation rate, but at the different levels. The effect of drug use history on substance rule violation rate in prison was stronger than that on non-substance rule violation rate, which provided support for the hypothesis formed above. In addition, most other independent variables in the models except race affected both substance rule violation rate and non-substance rule violation rate in the same direction or pattern. Black inmates were less likely to commit substance rule violations per month, but more likely to commit non-substance rule violations per month. The race differences found here were the same as those in Harer and Steffensmeier’s (1996). A possible explanation for the difference was the importation theory. The importation model assumed that since levels of non-substance criminal behavior, especially violence in the larger society, were much higher among Blacks than Whites, a high level of Black non-substance rule violations in prison also was expected (Harer & Steffensmeier, 1996; McNulty & Bellair, 2003).10 Also, since Whites had higher rates of polydrug use outside prison than Blacks (Flewelling, Ennett, Rachal, &

Theisen, 1993), a higher level of White substance rule violations inside prison was expected.
At the prison level, all predictors except the dummy variable minimum-security level were statistically significant in both substance and non-substance rule violation models. The direction of the relationships for the predictors, except the dummy variable prisons holding female inmates, also were the same for the two models. The effect of prisons holding female inmates was negative in the substance rule violation rate model while it was positive in the nonsubstance rule violation rate model. That is, female prisons had lower substance rule violation write-ups per month than male prisons, but had higher non-substance rule violation write-ups per month.
Were the gender differences in rule violation rates at the prison level consistent with the extant literature? If substance rule violations were considered as part of serious or major infractions (Pollock, 2002, p. 81), the result on substance rule violations was consistent with previous studies (see Pollock, 2002, pp. 80–83). Nonsubstance rule violations in this study included major and minor infractions. When minor infractions such as use of abusive language, horseplay, and failing to follow sanitary regulations were separated from major ones such as assaults, possession of a weapon, and escape, this study revealed that prisons holding female inmates had a much higher minor rule violation rate (.036) than prisons holding male inmates (.029), but a significant lower major rule violation rate (.036 versus .043).11 Finally, the full model explained more variance at the prison level for the nonsubstance rule violation model than for the substance rule violation model.
Summary and implications
This study examined the drug use history and prison rule violation relationships among inmates using multilevel analysis. It found that the drug use history led to higher substance rule violation rate and non-substance rule violation rate in prison. Also, the effect of pre-prison drug use on prison substance rule violations per month was stronger than that on prison non-substance rule violations per month. Other Level 1 variables such as age, race, and crime history were also significant predictors of both the substance and non-substance rule violations per month in prison. Furthermore, inmates who were younger, White, and had more prior sentences were more likely to commit substance rule violations per month while inmates who were younger, Black, and had more prior sentences were more likely to violate non-substance rules per month. At the prison level, the variables mean age, prison population, medium security level, prisons holding female inmates, and prisons holding both female and male inmates were significant predictors of both substance and non-substance rule violation rates.

