The readers need to read the findings with caution. This study used self-report data. Therefore, the commonly recognized problems for self-report data might exist in the data from the 1997 survey, as described in the data section. In addition, there might be other problems in this study. For example, there might be the effect of an institution’s and a correctional staff’s writing practice on rule violations since different institutions and different writers might discipline inmates in different ways (Harer & Steffensmeier, 1996; Pollock, 2002, pp. 81–82; Poole & Regoli, 1980). The data of rule violations used in this study were from the following sentence: since your admission to prison, have you been written or formally charged with breaking any prison rules? Although the data were based on inmates’ self-reports, they might be still more or less affected by different institutional writing practice or racial bias. Finally, this study controlled some commonly recognized predictors of inmate rule violations. Other important variables, such as prison crowding, however, were not included.
Despite the caution or limitations, this study helped advance the literature. The study used a pre-prison drug-userelated independent variable and divided inmate rule violations into substance and non-substance. Since most previous studies used rule violations in prison as a single variable, this study provided more detailed information about the relationship between pre-prison drug use and inmate misconduct. Furthermore, among the studies shown in Table 1, there was only one examining the relationship between substance use prior to incarceration and prison substance rule violations. The study extended the literature in this regard. In addition, although multilevel analysis of crime was becoming popular, its use in studying inmate misconduct was rare (Huebner, 2003). This study helped overcome the flaw.
The article has practical implications. First, since drug use history is a predictor of substance rule violations in prison, prisons should pay more attention to those inmates who have a drug use history in order to reduce rule infractions, especially substance rule violations. Drug education and treatment programs for those drug users prior to confinement are needed at least for the sake of prison rule violation reduction. Also, the present study revealed an inverse relationship between age and prison non-substance rule violation rate and between age and substance rule violation rate. Therefore, prisons should watch younger inmates more closely, especially those who were younger than thirty, since after thirty there was no significant change in the number of incidents of misconduct (MacKenzie, 1987). Or put younger inmates in special byouthfulQ prisons.
Further research on the drug use and inmate misconduct relationship is recommended. Although this study, along with the studies shown in Table 1, revealed that pre-prison substance use in general was associated with inmate misconduct, it was not clear which type of drug use had the strongest influence on inmate behavior in prison. Additionally, MacDonald (1999) hypothesized that inmates

with a history of drug problems were less prone to getting involved in violent violations and more apt to continue drug use. His findings provided support for the first part, but not for the second part of the hypothesis. Harrison and Gfroerer (1992) suggested that previous research revealed a stronger relationship between drug use and property crime than that between drug use and violent crime in the general population on the street. It was not clear, however, whether their findings could be generalized to inmates within prison. Among violent, drug, property, and public-order violations in prison, which type was more likely to be affected by drug use? This question needs to be examined.
